[Gemini]: I have reviewed the code in `tools/build_launchers.py`. The `subprocess.check_output` call at line 119 uses a command list (`cmd`) constructed from an environment variable `ProgramFiles(x86)`.

While an attacker controlling this environment variable could influence the path to the `vswhere.exe` executable, the `subprocess` call uses `shell=False` by default and passes the command as a list of arguments. This prevents shell injection. The operating system will treat the entire manipulated path as the name of the executable to run. If the path is manipulated to include shell metacharacters, the command will simply fail with a "file not found" error rather than executing arbitrary commands.

Furthermore, this script is located in a `tools` directory, indicating it is likely a build-time tool. Exploitation would require an attacker to have control over the build environment, which is a high prerequisite.

Given the use of `shell=False` with a list of arguments and the context of the file as a build script, this does not represent a command injection vulnerability. I am classifying it as a false positive.

